{
  "texts": [
    "Having found no difference in reappraisal quality as a function of incentives, we then checked whether increasing the incentives led to participants taking longer time in completing their reappraisal, to get some indication that incentives impacted participants' performance.",
    "We subset the data to only humans and regressed time spent on reappraisal as a function of incentive condition.",
    "We also added random intercepts for reappraiser and vignette.",
    "We did not find a significant difference between the participants in the no incentive condition compared to the 50% bonus condition (b = -0.187, t(400) = -.02, p =.98, R 2 =.02, 95% CI = [-15.07, 14.70]).",
    "We did, however, find that compared to the no incentive condition, participants in the 100% condition (b = 24.08, t(400) = 3.18, p =.002, R 2 =.02, 95% CI = [9.30, 38.87]) spent an additional 24 seconds on their reappraisal and participants in the 150% condition (b = 15.07, t(400) = 1.975, p =.049, R 2 =.02, 95% CI [0.15, 30.01]) spent an additional 15 seconds on their reappraisal."
  ]
}